---
name: git-box
description: This skill should be used whenever basic git procedures are required — committing, pushing, stashing, or switching branches. Trigger on phrases like "commit my changes", "commit and push", "save my work", "push this", "stash and switch to feat/x", "make 3 commits", or "commit the housekeeping, leave the rest". Use it for any commit / push / switch request even when the user doesn't say "git" explicitly — it routes the work to a guarded background agent instead of running git inline.
disable-model-invocation: true
allowed-tools: Bash(git status:*), Agent(git-commander)
---

# git-awesome

Route a git request to the **git-commander** background agent, which runs the work through
guarded verb commands and returns a structured report. The request may come from the user or
originate here. Read the status, turn the intent into an informative brief, hand it off, relay
the result. Message wording, emoji, and the git verbs themselves all happen downstream.

## Why a background agent

Running git inline burns the main context on mechanical work and exposes write operations to
the main agent. Delegating to git-commander keeps this session lean and confines git-write
authority to one agent that can only ever touch git (never files).

## Current state (auto-loaded)

!`git status -s -b -u`

That short status is enough to frame the brief. Avoid pulling fuller diffs here — the verb
commands load their own detail when they run.

## How to dispatch

1. **Read the status and the request together.** Status shows the branch, ahead/behind, and
   which files changed; the request says what to do with them.

2. **Write an informative brief.** For each action the request implies, state the _how and
   what_ so git-commander isn't left guessing:
   - commit — what to commit and how to group it
   - push — whether to push, and where (set upstream if there's none)
   - switch — which branch, and what to do with uncommitted work (e.g. dirty tree → stash,
     switch, pop)

   Fill any deficit from status. If the request omits the commit grouping, supply it from the
   changed files; if it asks for a switch but ignores a dirty tree, spell out the stash/pop.
   Don't decide message wording or stage anything — but leave nothing critical to chance.

3. **Launch git-commander** via the Agent tool, passing the brief. Let it dispatch the right
   verb commands and chain them as needed.

4. **Relay its report.** git-commander returns a structured summary (what it committed, push
   result, branch moves, anything blocked). Surface that to the user; if it flagged something
   needing judgment — an ambiguous split, a possible breaking change — bring that decision
   back to the user rather than answering on its behalf.

## Scope

git-commander agent covers **commit**, **push**, and **switch** work (switch / stash /
pop). Advanced git — merges, rebases, resets, history rewriting — is deliberately out of
scope; handle that directly in a guided session, not through this skill.
